00:06:02.510 --> 00:06:04.670
Her name was Ida Rolf.

00:06:04.670 --> 00:06:07.190
And she was a biochemist.

00:06:07.190 --> 00:06:11.450
But her passionate interest
was in human structures.

00:06:11.450 --> 00:06:14.240
So she developed
a manual therapy

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:17.270
she called structural
integration.

00:06:17.270 --> 00:06:21.260
And so her students and her
clients nicknamed it Rolfing.

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:25.580
She didn't much like
that, but now most of you

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:28.490
have heard of Rolfing, yes?

00:06:28.490 --> 00:06:33.950
So this therapy looks at the
body as living architecture

00:06:33.950 --> 00:06:37.460
which has been
distorted and diminished

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:42.290
by accidents, and
compensations, and poor use,

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:46.040
like sitting all
day without moving.

00:06:46.040 --> 00:06:49.640
She viewed pain as the
product, mostly the product

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:53.570
of imbalance structure.

00:06:53.570 --> 00:06:58.010
She had two revolutionary
ideas for the 60s.

00:06:58.010 --> 00:06:59.570
This expresses one of them.

00:06:59.570 --> 00:07:01.270
It's her logo.

00:07:01.270 --> 00:07:03.830
She thought that the body--

00:07:03.830 --> 00:07:07.340
she taught that the body
is organized by gravity

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:10.980
just like this building
is organized by gravity.

00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:14.690
So if the body
could be balanced,

00:07:14.690 --> 00:07:18.170
then gravity wouldn't
tear the body down

00:07:18.170 --> 00:07:22.050
but would in fact actually
contribute to health.

00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:23.910
So that was her first idea.

00:07:23.910 --> 00:07:27.660
Her second idea is that the
body's connective tissue

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:29.160
is plastic.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:31.170
It's able to change.

00:07:31.170 --> 00:07:33.690
So through
manipulation, she found

00:07:33.690 --> 00:07:37.230
that she could restore
balance to structures that had

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:40.680
become distorted and twisted.

00:07:40.680 --> 00:07:43.950
She was the first to
recognize the importance

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:47.980
of connective tissue,
what we now call fascia.

00:07:47.980 --> 00:07:51.090
She died in 1979.

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:54.060
But the first
research conference

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:56.730
about fascia, the
fascia congress,

00:07:56.730 --> 00:08:00.150
wasn't held until 2006.

00:08:00.150 --> 00:08:02.670
It happened at Harvard,
which was exciting for us

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:04.020
body workers.

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:07.260
But it was also attended
by many researchers

00:08:07.260 --> 00:08:10.530
from around the world
who had become interested

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:16.290
in this aspect of the body
that had mostly been ignored.

00:08:16.290 --> 00:08:20.250
So this is a simple
metaphor to share with you

00:08:20.250 --> 00:08:24.000
how fascia pervades your body.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:30.330
The rind of the orange is like
an all over body suit just

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:31.290
under your skin.

00:08:31.290 --> 00:08:34.919
If we peeled off all the skin,
we would see a fascia layer.

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:37.980
It's literally a body suit.

00:08:37.980 --> 00:08:41.400
It contains everything else.

00:08:41.400 --> 00:08:46.890
And underneath that are
the segments of the orange,

00:08:46.890 --> 00:08:51.720
represent the various organs and
muscles and larger structures

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:57.000
that each have a containing
membrane, as well as blood

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.200
vessels, and nerves, and bones,
all have a wrapping of fascia

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:02.640
around them.

00:09:02.640 --> 00:09:06.720
And all of this
fascia is continuous.

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:09.270
And the little orange
bits inside the segments,

00:09:09.270 --> 00:09:12.750
you know how your fingers get
sticky when you eat an orange--

00:09:12.750 --> 00:09:16.230
so those little bits
represent cells.

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:22.080
So each cell in your body
has its own fascial membrane.

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:24.600
So it's been suggested
that if you took out

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:28.320
everything else from the
body except the fascia,

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:31.300
you'd still have a
recognizable human shape.

00:09:35.220 --> 00:09:39.060
This is an 18th century
painting of a dissection.

00:09:39.060 --> 00:09:42.870
It hangs in the Wellcome
Library in London.

00:09:42.870 --> 00:09:47.880
So until recently, anatomists
stripped away the fascia

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:51.180
and discarded it so they could
look at the interesting things,

00:09:51.180 --> 00:09:56.580
the liver and the brain and the
circulatory system and so on.

00:09:56.580 --> 00:09:57.540
And that was good.

00:09:57.540 --> 00:09:59.250
We needed that.

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:01.800
But what it did was
perpetuate the idea

00:10:01.800 --> 00:10:06.540
that your body is made up
of an assemblage of parts,

00:10:06.540 --> 00:10:12.000
rather than that it develops
out of wholeness, which I'll

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.780
talk about a little more later.

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:22.260
This photo is an endoscopic
image of living fascia.

00:10:22.260 --> 00:10:26.280
It's magnified 130
times, and it's

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:29.510
the work of a man named
Jean-Claude Guiberteau.

00:10:29.510 --> 00:10:31.920
He's a French microsurgeon.

00:10:31.920 --> 00:10:34.420
He uses endoscopy in his work.

00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:36.660
So this means putting
little cameras and lights

00:10:36.660 --> 00:10:41.520
and microscopes inside
the living tissue.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:47.500
So he has been so awed by what
he saw that he's developed

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:49.800
a collection of these images.

00:10:49.800 --> 00:10:55.700
And I can give you his
web site after the talk.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:57.785
Appreciate these
geometric forms.

00:11:00.365 --> 00:11:05.650
The immune system--
sorry, the fascia system

00:11:05.650 --> 00:11:09.520
is now being
studied the same way

00:11:09.520 --> 00:11:12.580
that the immune system and
the circulatory system and all

00:11:12.580 --> 00:11:14.810
the other systems
are being studied.

00:11:14.810 --> 00:11:20.020
So there are three main
constituents of fascia.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:24.280
One is collagen. It's
like protein fibers which,

00:11:24.280 --> 00:11:26.890
when they're woven
tightly together,

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:30.280
have the strength of steel.

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:32.980
There are also elastic
fibers that you

00:11:32.980 --> 00:11:37.840
could stretch to 100%
of their capacity,

00:11:37.840 --> 00:11:43.870
and then they could relax back
without deforming their shape.

00:11:43.870 --> 00:11:46.540
And the third constituent
is a watery matrix,

00:11:46.540 --> 00:11:51.430
something like egg white,
kind of mucousy stuff.

00:11:51.430 --> 00:11:53.830
And they're swimming
in their cells

00:11:53.830 --> 00:11:59.030
like immune cells, and fat
cells, and nerve cells.

00:11:59.030 --> 00:12:02.650
So this was very interesting
to us in the body work world,

00:12:02.650 --> 00:12:05.410
that there were nerve
cells in fascia.

00:12:05.410 --> 00:12:08.650
We knew from doing
Dr. Rolf's work

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:11.110
that there was some
kind of communication

00:12:11.110 --> 00:12:12.130
through the fascia.

00:12:12.130 --> 00:12:17.870
But we had all kinds of other
ideas about what was doing it.

00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:21.610
And there are actually sensory
nerve fibers in the fascia.

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:28.990
In fact, estimated six times
as many nerve fibers in fascia

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.190
as in muscle.

00:12:31.190 --> 00:12:36.670
So when you think you're moving
through your neuromuscular

00:12:36.670 --> 00:12:40.510
system, it's actually
the fascial system

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:46.270
that is allowing that to
come into full expression.

00:12:46.270 --> 00:12:50.110
A lot of these nerve
sensors in the fascia

00:12:50.110 --> 00:12:52.660
are called interoceptors.

00:12:52.660 --> 00:12:57.560
That means they tell you what's
going on inside your body.

00:12:57.560 --> 00:13:02.980
So when you feel bloated, or
you have a tickle or an itch,

00:13:02.980 --> 00:13:06.880
or you have sexual
arousal, or air hunger,

00:13:06.880 --> 00:13:10.300
all of these kinds of
sensations in your body

00:13:10.300 --> 00:13:14.500
are because of the
interoceptors in your fascia.

00:13:14.500 --> 00:13:18.610
So you might think
that interoception

00:13:18.610 --> 00:13:20.620
is the way you know
that you have a body.

00:13:26.380 --> 00:13:29.630
A lot of different
textures fascia can assume.

00:13:29.630 --> 00:13:32.010
It can have the
transparency of glass,

00:13:32.010 --> 00:13:35.480
so your corneas are fascia.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:38.800
Your breasts are fascia,
full of lots of fat cells.

00:13:42.680 --> 00:13:47.270
When you have a scar, that's the
collagen fibers woven tightly

00:13:47.270 --> 00:13:48.860
together to protect the wound.

00:13:51.500 --> 00:13:55.680
It's also very fluid,
gelatin like, slidey--

00:13:55.680 --> 00:13:56.610
slippy-slidey.

00:13:56.610 --> 00:14:01.520
So when we watch our most
beautiful athletes and dancers,

00:14:01.520 --> 00:14:06.830
what we're seeing is not just
their superb neuromuscular

00:14:06.830 --> 00:14:11.050
system, but also the health
of their fascial system.

00:14:11.050 --> 00:14:13.320
Note the last point.

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:16.670
Stress and immobility
dehydrates your fascia.

00:14:16.670 --> 00:14:18.770
It makes it stiff.

00:14:18.770 --> 00:14:21.200
It makes you stiff.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:24.110
So stress and immobility
are the characteristics

00:14:24.110 --> 00:14:26.360
of the modern workplace.

00:14:26.360 --> 00:14:29.360
The powerful leaping
of a kangaroo

00:14:29.360 --> 00:14:33.110
is due not just to its
powerful leg muscles,

00:14:33.110 --> 00:14:37.440
but to the high percentage
of fascia in its body.

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:43.200
So when those elastic fibers
stretch through movement,

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:46.700
it stores kinetic energy
which is then released

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:48.260
and the kangaroo rebounds.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:54.430
Interesting thing here is
that our bodies, human bodies,

00:14:54.430 --> 00:15:00.830
have the same high percentage of
fascia in them as the kangaroo.

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:03.250
So if you think about
that, it's clear

00:15:03.250 --> 00:15:09.760
that we're made for leaping and
running, and not for sitting.

