But if you make
just a pinch of skin

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:53.390
with your finger pads,
just a gentle pinch of skin

00:15:53.390 --> 00:15:57.520
and pull up on it, and
when the video starts

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:01.840
you could slowly let
down on the pinch

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:05.720
and then draw up again
as the video goes up.

00:16:10.690 --> 00:16:13.280
Now it's coming down, you're
letting go of your pinch.

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:17.430
And you're pulling up.

00:16:23.540 --> 00:16:27.980
These images are so amazing.

00:16:27.980 --> 00:16:31.610
So that kind of shape
shifting is going on

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:35.300
inside your body with every
movement that you make--

00:16:35.300 --> 00:16:37.640
while you're
breathing, while you're

00:16:37.640 --> 00:16:42.800
brushing your teeth, while
you're rolling over in bed.

00:16:42.800 --> 00:16:48.680
This is another one of
Jean Guimberteau's videos.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:50.964
And it takes place
in the same place,

00:16:50.964 --> 00:16:52.130
but it's a little different.

00:16:52.130 --> 00:16:54.680
It's magnified 10 times.

00:16:54.680 --> 00:16:57.290
The other one was
magnified 20 times.

00:16:57.290 --> 00:17:00.110
And this one is also a
deeper place in the forearm.

00:17:00.110 --> 00:17:03.530
So take the palm of one
hand and press it lightly

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:06.829
against the skin just
below your elbow,

00:17:06.829 --> 00:17:11.540
as if those two layers of skin
were adhered to each other.

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:14.960
And then what you do is
just a gentle pulling down

00:17:14.960 --> 00:17:17.827
of this skin toward your wrist.

00:17:17.827 --> 00:17:19.910
And you might be able to
feel that you're not just

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:24.290
pulling on skin, but other
layers are moving underneath.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:30.570
And then draw up toward your
elbow with that same thing.

00:17:30.570 --> 00:17:34.220
So that's what's going on here.

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:45.580
The bubbles that you see are
because of the difference

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:49.150
in pressure between
what's going on

00:17:49.150 --> 00:17:55.740
inside the incision and the air
outside, pressure differential.

00:17:59.490 --> 00:18:04.940
Notice the changing direction
of these microfibers,

00:18:04.940 --> 00:18:08.310
how they keep
re-orienting themselves,

00:18:08.310 --> 00:18:09.746
changing their polarities.

00:18:16.460 --> 00:18:20.330
It's like a crystalline
kaleidoscope inside you.

00:18:25.060 --> 00:18:29.110
So you keep your fascia
healthy by moving.

00:18:29.110 --> 00:18:33.050
And the important thing is
movement in many directions,

00:18:33.050 --> 00:18:37.660
so multi-directional movement,
not forward movement that's

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:38.860
repetitive.

00:18:38.860 --> 00:18:44.080
So if you had a choice
between going to a dance jam,

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:49.000
or working out on an Exercycle,
for the benefit of your fascia

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.310
you need to go dancing--

00:18:51.310 --> 00:18:54.970
probably for other reasons, too.

00:18:54.970 --> 00:18:57.830
Whole body stretches
are good for the fascia,

00:18:57.830 --> 00:19:01.610
so that pandiculation
that we did before.

00:19:01.610 --> 00:19:03.850
As long as it's a whole
body stretch and not

00:19:03.850 --> 00:19:07.090
just this kind of stretch
of isolated muscles

00:19:07.090 --> 00:19:08.470
that people do.

00:19:08.470 --> 00:19:11.020
That's a different thing.

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:15.430
Gentle bouncy movements, so
if you went folk dancing that

00:19:15.430 --> 00:19:17.110
would be good for your fascia.

00:19:17.110 --> 00:19:21.430
Not big leaps, but
just gentle bouncing.

00:19:21.430 --> 00:19:24.010
Micromovements-- we'll be
doing some micromovements

00:19:24.010 --> 00:19:25.790
in a few minutes.

00:19:25.790 --> 00:19:29.740
These are small movements that
you can barely, barely see.

00:19:29.740 --> 00:19:31.600
Certainly you can feel them.

00:19:31.600 --> 00:19:34.120
Massage can help.

00:19:34.120 --> 00:19:38.950
All of these suggestions
don't cover strength training

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:39.920
or aerobic training.

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:41.710
You need that too, of course.

00:19:41.710 --> 00:19:44.220
This is fascia specific.

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:47.650
This image of an embryo
is at development

00:19:47.650 --> 00:19:51.070
about four to five weeks.

00:19:51.070 --> 00:19:55.780
But fascia emerges in
embryonic development earlier

00:19:55.780 --> 00:19:59.210
than this, at about two weeks.

00:19:59.210 --> 00:20:02.420
So fascia researchers
suggest that muscles,

00:20:02.420 --> 00:20:07.360
bones, organs, in fact
all other living tissue,

00:20:07.360 --> 00:20:11.830
may in fact be specializations
within the unified

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:14.800
medium of fascia.

00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:17.500
So that's a very
different way of thinking

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:20.560
about how we evolved
than the idea

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:23.065
that we're just a bunch
of parts stuck together.

00:20:25.700 --> 00:20:30.890
Everything in the fascial system
is interconnected and fluid,

00:20:30.890 --> 00:20:33.990
and you can feel this
when you breathe.

00:20:33.990 --> 00:20:36.050
So let's try.

00:20:36.050 --> 00:20:38.570
So if you would
just be comfortable,

00:20:38.570 --> 00:20:41.240
and if you feel like
closing your eyes sometimes

00:20:41.240 --> 00:20:45.020
that helps you feel
your body more readily.

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:49.520
Just go inside and feel the
sort of swelling and settling

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:54.530
of your chest as you
inhale and exhale.

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:58.600
Just a little expansion,
and then diminishment.

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:07.780
And you could feel it, probably
also in your belly a little,

00:21:07.780 --> 00:21:10.270
puffing up and letting go.

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:19.570
And then turn your attention
to your shoulder blades,

00:21:19.570 --> 00:21:23.140
and see if you can feel
them sliding maybe apart

00:21:23.140 --> 00:21:27.890
from each other, maybe up
a little bit as you inhale

00:21:27.890 --> 00:21:29.410
and resting down.

00:21:32.090 --> 00:21:39.020
Shoulder blades move apart
so the rib cage can expand.

00:21:39.020 --> 00:21:43.880
And then drop your awareness
down into your forearms.

00:21:43.880 --> 00:21:48.770
There are two bones in your
forearms, in each forearm.

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:50.870
And there is a
membrane in between.

00:21:50.870 --> 00:21:56.600
So imagine that membrane
swelling and settling

00:21:56.600 --> 00:21:57.880
as you breathe in and out.

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:08.350
And then come down
into your lower legs.

00:22:08.350 --> 00:22:12.820
See if you can go that far
down and feel your fascia

00:22:12.820 --> 00:22:17.505
moving as you breathe, in
between the lower leg bones.

00:22:24.300 --> 00:22:28.080
It's interesting
that the place where

00:22:28.080 --> 00:22:31.470
you feel a sensation
in your brain,

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:34.660
is the same place that
you imagine a sensation,

00:22:34.660 --> 00:22:36.280
the sensory cortex.

00:22:36.280 --> 00:22:39.720
So it doesn't matter if you
think you're only imagining it.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:42.140
It's good enough.

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:45.330
Drop down into your soles.

00:22:45.330 --> 00:22:47.610
See if you can feel
that when you inhale,

00:22:47.610 --> 00:22:51.555
there's the slightest
pressure down into your shoes.

00:22:56.700 --> 00:23:00.510
And let yourself imagine
that tensile matrix

00:23:00.510 --> 00:23:02.130
that we saw earlier.

00:23:02.130 --> 00:23:05.910
Imagine it throughout
your whole body,

00:23:05.910 --> 00:23:08.980
all those little fibers
changing their orientation.

00:23:14.480 --> 00:23:17.620
Thank you, you can
open your eyes.

00:23:17.620 --> 00:23:19.940
Could you feel a bit?

00:23:19.940 --> 00:23:21.140
Imagine you felt?

00:23:25.210 --> 00:23:28.610
But it will be a while
before our culture

00:23:28.610 --> 00:23:33.470
learns to see the body as
continuous and connected.

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:37.340
We think of the body
in bits and pieces.

00:23:37.340 --> 00:23:41.660
When we have a pain, we
blame it on an isolated part.

00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:45.500
We exercise isolated,
separate muscles.

00:23:45.500 --> 00:23:50.030
We do lap pulls and ab crunches.

00:23:50.030 --> 00:23:54.530
And when we want to
portray images of power,

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:57.100
we just add more
and stiffer parts.

00:24:02.560 --> 00:24:06.880
This model suggests
a way of conceiving

00:24:06.880 --> 00:24:09.760
how the body is held together.

00:24:09.760 --> 00:24:13.720
So it is, you're seeing
struts held in place

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:17.230
by a network of tension.

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:20.020
In terms of the body,
the elastic lines

00:24:20.020 --> 00:24:26.230
are your soft tissues and
the struts are your bones.

00:24:26.230 --> 00:24:32.540
Ideally, your bones are floating
in a network of soft tissue.

00:24:32.540 --> 00:24:38.360
This architectural principle
is called tensional integrity,

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:42.710
or as Buckminster Fuller
called it, tensegrity.

00:24:42.710 --> 00:24:45.200
And you can see
that if you change

00:24:45.200 --> 00:24:48.710
the tension in just
one of those strings,

00:24:48.710 --> 00:24:51.890
the whole structure
would change its shape,

00:24:51.890 --> 00:24:54.950
change its orientation
a little bit.

00:24:54.950 --> 00:24:57.410
And that's true inside us.

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:58.680
That's how we work, too.

00:25:02.290 --> 00:25:05.650
Even the vertebrae, the
individual vertebrae

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:08.890
in your spine, can
float and respond

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:12.010
inside this network of tension.

00:25:12.010 --> 00:25:14.080
But we don't think
of it that way.

00:25:14.080 --> 00:25:18.160
We talk about the
spine as a column.

00:25:18.160 --> 00:25:21.670
On the right, you see
a tensegrity tower.

00:25:21.670 --> 00:25:26.090
It's a sculpture by a man
named Kenneth Snelson,

00:25:26.090 --> 00:25:29.560
in the Washington National
Mall in Washington.

00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:34.090
And you can see that it's more
similar in quality to the spine

00:25:34.090 --> 00:25:38.320
than the Washington Monument is.

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:44.170
So how do we learn to behave
more like biotensegrities

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:46.260
and less like stacks of bricks?

00:25:48.880 --> 00:25:52.360
Well, it's helpful to
think or imagine back

00:25:52.360 --> 00:25:55.120
to prehistoric times,
how the body might

00:25:55.120 --> 00:25:57.370
have functioned in those days.

00:26:00.230 --> 00:26:05.180
So our prehistoric ancestors had
to move their bodies in order

00:26:05.180 --> 00:26:07.350
to survive.

00:26:07.350 --> 00:26:09.920
So you could imagine
what kind of movements

00:26:09.920 --> 00:26:13.130
they might have had to do
to kill their breakfast

00:26:13.130 --> 00:26:15.170
or herd their cattle.

00:26:15.170 --> 00:26:19.100
So they'd be crouching,
or throwing, or digging,

00:26:19.100 --> 00:26:22.160
or lifting, carrying
stuff, and none of that

00:26:22.160 --> 00:26:25.190
would be predictable
or repetitive.

00:26:25.190 --> 00:26:29.780
So constantly changing
movement, large body movements.

00:26:29.780 --> 00:26:36.110
Also, they would be traveling
in bare feet, or skins,

00:26:36.110 --> 00:26:41.870
on uneven terrain which had
pebbles and thorns in it.

00:26:41.870 --> 00:26:44.570
So their feet had
to be extremely

00:26:44.570 --> 00:26:46.475
mobile to navigate the ground.

00:26:49.130 --> 00:26:51.860
And that mobility in
the feet would play up

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:53.960
through the whole
fascial system,

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:56.780
so every joint in
the body would have

00:26:56.780 --> 00:26:59.990
to respond to the
movements of the feet.

00:26:59.990 --> 00:27:05.370
So that's an example of
micromovement in a sense.

00:27:05.370 --> 00:27:07.970
And these movements,
large and small,

00:27:07.970 --> 00:27:11.540
must have kept their
fascia healthy.

00:27:11.540 --> 00:27:15.460
I like to think that, anyway.

00:27:15.460 --> 00:27:19.450
And they had to have a panoramic
view of their surroundings.

00:27:19.450 --> 00:27:24.450
They had to have
360 degree awareness

00:27:24.450 --> 00:27:26.070
through all their senses--

00:27:26.070 --> 00:27:36.380
through hearing, sight,
olfactory, feeling sense.

00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:40.650
And it's as if they had eyes
in the backs of their heads.

00:27:40.650 --> 00:27:44.160
But with us, we're
always looking forward--

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:47.100
this way, this way, forward.

00:27:47.100 --> 00:27:49.410
So let's practice something.

00:27:49.410 --> 00:27:54.600
I want to see if you can feel
the benefit of having a more

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:57.760
broad peripheral awareness.

00:27:57.760 --> 00:28:00.699
So you need to stand up again.

00:28:00.699 --> 00:28:01.740
So you could pandiculate.

00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:02.685
It's a good idea.

00:28:05.860 --> 00:28:08.280
There are certain noises
that go with pandiculation.

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:12.645
Yeah, it could be louder.

00:28:16.200 --> 00:28:20.580
OK, so find a detail somewhere
around you-- not a person,

00:28:20.580 --> 00:28:22.470
but something you could look at.

00:28:22.470 --> 00:28:27.480
Could be the screen, or it could
be exit sign, or a thermostat,

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:32.010
some detail that you could
gaze at with a lot of intensity

00:28:32.010 --> 00:28:37.110
of vision that you have to
write a report about this thing,

00:28:37.110 --> 00:28:39.580
and it's due tomorrow and
your job depends on it.

00:28:39.580 --> 00:28:41.250
So really look.

00:28:41.250 --> 00:28:41.870
Look hard.

00:28:45.270 --> 00:28:46.080
Keep that.

00:28:46.080 --> 00:28:48.630
Keep that intensity.

00:28:48.630 --> 00:28:50.790
And notice your breathing.

00:28:50.790 --> 00:28:55.030
Notice where it's
located in your body.

00:28:55.030 --> 00:29:00.170
Notice the relationship between
your torso and your neck

00:29:00.170 --> 00:29:02.940
and jaw and head.

00:29:02.940 --> 00:29:05.205
Notice the sensation
in your eyes.

00:29:09.750 --> 00:29:15.590
Notice where your
weight is on your feet,

00:29:15.590 --> 00:29:18.350
and how big you feel in general.

00:29:18.350 --> 00:29:19.820
OK, so relax that.

00:29:19.820 --> 00:29:23.100
Just shake it out.

00:29:23.100 --> 00:29:27.620
We want to neutralize ourselves
so we can do something else.

00:29:27.620 --> 00:29:28.130
Thank you.

00:29:28.130 --> 00:29:31.220
So now, put your
fingers out like this.

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:32.690
Wiggle your fingers.

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:36.140
And you can see, peripherally,
still looking at me,

00:29:36.140 --> 00:29:38.234
you can still see what's
beyond your fingers.

00:29:38.234 --> 00:29:39.650
You could put your
hands down now.

00:29:39.650 --> 00:29:43.490
And just keep
looking so that you

00:29:43.490 --> 00:29:47.450
have a sense of the
periphery of the room.

00:29:47.450 --> 00:29:50.480
And you also notice something
about what's above your head.

00:29:50.480 --> 00:29:52.130
You can feel it.

00:29:52.130 --> 00:29:56.510
And because you walked in here,
you know what's behind you.

00:29:56.510 --> 00:30:01.790
You have a kinesthetic
memory of what's behind you.

00:30:01.790 --> 00:30:08.330
So you have a broad
perceptual awareness.

00:30:08.330 --> 00:30:11.450
So I want you to see if
you can keep that, and then

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:14.300
turn and look at
your same object

00:30:14.300 --> 00:30:17.510
that you looked at before.

00:30:17.510 --> 00:30:20.840
And I'd like to suggest some
things that may or may not

00:30:20.840 --> 00:30:22.622
be different.

00:30:22.622 --> 00:30:25.080
They're different when I teach
this to different people.

00:30:25.080 --> 00:30:27.800
So I think it's
possible that you're

00:30:27.800 --> 00:30:32.480
breathing lower in your
rib cage, not so high

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:33.340
in your upper chest.

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:40.610
I think your eyes feel
softer, and that you feel

00:30:40.610 --> 00:30:43.910
less merged with that object.

00:30:43.910 --> 00:30:46.430
There's more of a
sense of you being here

00:30:46.430 --> 00:30:47.720
and it being over there.

00:30:50.600 --> 00:30:55.220
Also, it's possible that you
see the object in its context,

00:30:55.220 --> 00:30:58.280
so your report is going
to be more interesting.

00:31:03.750 --> 00:31:07.320
So great, thank you very much.

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:12.910
I like to think of this as
tensegrity of perception.

00:31:12.910 --> 00:31:16.200
So what I mean by that is, by
having these little feelers out

00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:20.910
in all directions, you
establish a virtual network

00:31:20.910 --> 00:31:24.900
in the space, a virtual
network of potential directions

00:31:24.900 --> 00:31:28.920
of movement through
the space that actually

00:31:28.920 --> 00:31:31.260
helps support your body.

00:31:31.260 --> 00:31:34.950
I think you've felt that you had
better posture the second time,

00:31:34.950 --> 00:31:36.710
yes?

00:31:36.710 --> 00:31:39.180
You were bigger.

00:31:39.180 --> 00:31:45.390
Yeah, and so this awareness
of our surroundings

00:31:45.390 --> 00:31:47.820
helps our bodies
open up on the inside

00:31:47.820 --> 00:31:50.710
as well as on the outside.

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:52.170
So we have better posture.

00:31:52.170 --> 00:31:55.050
We actually have
more strength, which

00:31:55.050 --> 00:31:59.620
if you stay for the little class
afterwards I can show you that.

00:31:59.620 --> 00:32:04.680
So picture the movements you
make to get to work, to get up,

00:32:04.680 --> 00:32:06.790
get your breakfast, go to work.

00:32:06.790 --> 00:32:09.700
And the movements that you
make while you're at work.

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:13.120
It might be different at
Google than it is other places,

00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:18.900
but generally in offices
your movements are curtailed.

00:32:18.900 --> 00:32:21.150
You don't have a
lot of movement.

00:32:21.150 --> 00:32:24.270
Most of it is in
the forward plane.

00:32:24.270 --> 00:32:27.540
And your perceptions
are narrowed.

00:32:27.540 --> 00:32:32.250
So I think it's
important for us humans

00:32:32.250 --> 00:32:36.510
to acknowledge that the
amazing conveniences that we're

00:32:36.510 --> 00:32:39.720
living with in this
time may actually

00:32:39.720 --> 00:32:44.700
be diminishing our body's
natural capacity for movement

00:32:44.700 --> 00:32:46.780
and perception.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:50.040
So we want to change
that, I think.

00:32:50.040 --> 00:32:54.660
What can we do about sitting
and standing and moving

00:32:54.660 --> 00:32:58.120
in the workplace now?

00:32:58.120 --> 00:33:02.640
So an expensive ergonomic
chair is not the answer,

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:05.790
because it doesn't
guarantee that you're going

00:33:05.790 --> 00:33:08.790
to sit in it in a balanced way.

00:33:08.790 --> 00:33:13.810
This chair, like many, has a dip
towards the back of the seat.

00:33:13.810 --> 00:33:18.360
So that dip tends to roll
the pelvis back and invite

00:33:18.360 --> 00:33:22.410
your spine to lean
against the backrest.

00:33:22.410 --> 00:33:24.330
Most modern chairs
are like this.

00:33:24.330 --> 00:33:27.810
You slide back.

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:29.220
Car seats are the worst.

00:33:29.220 --> 00:33:32.250
Those bucket seats are
designed to prevent movement.

00:33:36.670 --> 00:33:42.650
If human spines don't need back
support when we're standing up,

00:33:42.650 --> 00:33:46.220
